If the test is positive, I won’t be devastated. People who are diagnosed with Lynch early have good outcomes, as it means access to early colonoscopies and other screenings. It’s also likely to mean a hysterectomy in my early 40s and/or when my family is complete.

BRCA mutations are well known about these days, but we are looking for a specific variety of Lynch Syndrome, which is probably more common. I already know there is a 50% chance I have this. It means an increased chance of bowel and endometrial cancers amongst other things.

So this week I get to fill a tube with saliva, then send it off to the USA. A few weeks later I will find out if I have a genetic mutation which greatly increases my chances of certain cancers. https://t.co/ZokUi8UL5b
